segments.text: Tell us something about your early life, including the names of your parents, the dates of their birth and death, and the place of their birth and death, if you know them.
If you don't know them, that's OK, too.
And where they were born, where you were born, and the schools you went to before you went to A&M.
Well, now, do I start off by saying my name is Thaddeus Ansley?
That's fine, yes.
At Texas A&M, I'm known as Thad.
A Ansley, in some way a mix up in my transcribing my high school grades to Texas A&M.
Thaddeus, no middle initial Ansley, became Thad A, initial only Ansley.
My father, Benjamin Thomas Ansley, Jr., was born in 1870 in Johnson County, Texas.
My mother, Goldie Fanny Nally Ansley, was born in West Station.
That's in Ellis County, Texas.
I was in 1879.
I was the fifth child and the fifth consecutive son of B.T.
and Goldie Ansley was born in Channing, Texas, the home of the XIT Ranch, in 1906.
Channing, Texas is in Hartley County.

From in 1908, my father, my father at the time was, had been superintendent of schools at Channing, Texas and then he became the land agent for the XIT Ranch and sold it, made a lot of money, made $50,000.
He had $50,000 in cash and went to Plainview, Texas and established the third national bank.
built the building and is still standing on the square there and built a nine-room house on a quarter of a block of land.
I believe it's been moved recently.
In 1908, we moved to Plainview, Texas.
And my father ran the Ansel Land Cattle Company there and two other children.
The sixth child was a girl and the seventh child
was a boy, Benjamin Thomas Ansley III, who is also a Texas Aggie, the class of 45, were born in Plainview.
And we moved to Amarillo in Potter County, Texas in 1917.
And that has been my home since then.
Since 17.
And did you go to school?
I went to Amarillo High School.
I pride myself in the fact that I was a member of the first Amarillo Golden Sandstorm
baseball team.
I lettered in baseball and basketball at my mother's high school.
Are either of your parents still living?
No, my father and mother are both dead.
My father lived to be 86 and my mother to be about 80.
factors were involved in your choice of Texas A&M as a school?
My uh one of my neighbor boys brother worked for the county here for the the Potter County engineer.
The Potter County engineer was Colonel O.A.
Seward who is from Washington County and a class of ought nine I believe or one of the early classes of Texas A&M and
We liked him and we fell in love with his description of Texas A&M.
We decided to be civil engineers.
Incidentally, I am now in the dry cleaning business.
My college roommate who lives here now is an independent rancher investments, but he has never practiced a day of civil, neither of us have ever practiced a day of civil engineering.
So it was a personal acquaintance type thing.
That's right.
I think so.
You had never been to the campus before.
No, I had never been to campus.
Of course, that was a day and a half or a two-day train ride from Amarillo to College Station at that time.
That's a pretty good day's car drive today, even with good highway.
That's right.
What were your first reactions to the campus when you arrived there as an incoming freshman?
college roommate, who was also my neighbor here in Amarillo, had gone on ahead to meet some friends in Houston.
And he met me at the station at the old H&TC station.
Well, that's good enough, H&TC station and college station.
And one of the biggest disappointments in my life was that I knew that there would be 200 people, 200 sophomores to meet me
at the station at A&M with the board.
Of course they weren't, and this old old person I knew in the world there was my 2B college roommate, and he met me at the station.
We took that long walk from the station up to the main building, and two country boys you've never seen, we went to looking around, and we asked them if they knew where we could find Dobbin.
Now Dobbin happened to be a man named
an umbrella man that we knew down there that was in Calgary.
He was a senior.
And they says, who do you mean?
I said, well, don't you know Dobbin Dodson?
They says, you mean Major Dodson.
So anyway, we found out that who we called Dobbin or Ham was known as Dusty Dodson at Texas A&M.
And he was a major, and he finally, this placement.
put us in the room in Milner Hall.
So I spent my first night at Texas A&M in Milner Hall, and once again, I must say that I was disappointed.
There wasn't any haze, and they left us alone.
We heard lots of noise and lots of things going on, but they didn't bother us.
Did you have to go through any special procedures to get into the school?
I mean, did you have to apply in advance or did you just appear on the scene?
No, our grades were sent ahead of us in transcript.
I don't know whether it was called transcript then or not.
But did the school ask Amarillo High School for them, or did you ask Amarillo High School to send the grades?
We asked Amarillo High School to send them.
Uh-huh.
So they had reason to believe, at least at A&M, that you were coming.
That's right.
And your grades were acceptable to them, so they let you in.
So then did you register?
You got there one day.
Did you register the next day?
I do not know.
I can't answer that question.
What I mean is...
I would say within the next day or two.
And then you started classes right after that.
Started classes the next month.
Could you describe a typical day while you were there?

What I mean is, tell us something about the procedure of getting up, the time you got up, the time you spent in classes, what you did otherwise other than going to class, what time you went to bed, and what procedure there was involved in going to bed.
They had puttees or leggings, I believe, wrapped leggings when I was at Texas A&M.
And so we set our alarm clock for 30 minutes ahead of the time.
I've even forgotten what time it was, but I'm sure it was about 5.30 in the morning.
We had to get up 30 minutes before everyone else to wrap our leggings because we didn't know how.
This was the fish.
Yeah, the freshmen, yes, were fish.
And...
We met revelry at some unearthly hour to a high school boy that had always been pampered at home and lived within a block of the schoolhouse, so I never was a very early riser.
Likewise, my college roommate who lived next door, we both lived within 100 yards of the schoolhouse.
After Reveille and Drill, which I kind of associate that with part of A&M, you learn to

right there you learn to become a part of a squad and you learn that that's the best squad in the in the world and then it's your platoons the best platoon in the world and then it's your uh company's the best it goes on kind of like that i think that's one of the reasons for loyalty to any and they teach you they start at the beginning to try to endeavor to do something or make the best of things that they are
Of course, after coming back to the room, then we got further dressed, I presume, and marched to our meals, breakfast.
After breakfast in the mess hall, we could idle or walk back to the dormitory.
It seemed like as a freshman, all classes began at 8 o'clock.
I don't know whether that's not true, but it seemed that way.
I couldn't tell you now how many hours.
It seemed like 17 hours, but that's... 17 class hours a week.
17 class hours a week, but that's immaterial.
As an engineering student, we took... All engineering students took basic...
one basic subject or basic subject.
I had to be in section 26.
I believe my roommate was in class section 25.

I don't know whether it was according to intelligence test of which the intelligence test at Texas A&M was my first intelligence test and it was a big shock to me because I had never had a test of that kind that I know of.
So I imagine we were placed in sections according to our rate on our intelligence test.
Did you have to reform in companies for noon meal?
Oh yes, we then we at noon we come back to the dormitories and made formation and marched to the mess hall and once again we could amble back to our rooms and do most anything we wanted to.
As a freshman, there was very little idle time.
There was always something doing and studying.
I thought I was an athlete, and I had gotten through high school probably for that reason.
At Texas A&M, I studied five hours every day.
The only way that I could get by, I think I finally learned how to study.
That happens to a lot of people.
As a matter of fact, I think probably to most people when they get out of high school into college, they have to learn how to study, first of all.
And it was very difficult for me.
And I was taking civil engineering, which I know now that I was not qualified to.
parts of it.
I was like mathematics, and I thought the civil engineer would be for me, but I found out since it wasn't.
Then what about during the afternoon?
Did you have labs?
We had labs, of course.
I know all freshman students had to take fish chemistry, of which four years later most of them were still taking fish chemistry.
and had laboratory, three hours of laboratory a week and two hours of class work is the way I remember it.
We had a little bit of mechanical engineering and they told us, we called it iron pounding.
They told us some fundamentals about brazing metals or welding metals together and we called it iron pounding.
of which I'm still not qualified to do.
After my freshman year, I bought my father a chisel that I made now iron pounding.
And he said, well, when I brought it back to him, he said, well, that's a $600 chisel.
That's what he'd call it.
He'd send me to school, Texas A&M, $600.
$630, I believe, was my expenses from the day I left Amarillo until the day I came back to Amarillo in June.
That even included the Christmas holidays.
I spent $630, and I never worked a minute in my freshman year.
Did you come home for Christmas?
I came home for Christmas.
Of course, as I say, it was at least a day and a half and probably two days train ride from College Station.
We would ride the train, H&TC up to Fort Worth,
and then get to Fort Worth and Denver from Fort Worth to Amarillo.
One of our great experiences was football trips, getting to make the football trips to Austin and to Waco for the Baylor games, which is quite an experience for a country boy.
At that time, 2,300 cadets all on the trains, which would take four special trains to haul us.
Did each cadet have to pay for a ticket on the train?
Oh, yes, yes.
Of course, not all of us paid.
I guess you heard some pretty good stories about how we hit them on the, what is it, the blinds and one way or another.
Anyway...
You get that many boys together, there's a lot of conniving.
Yeah, and then you paid admission to the game too.
That's right, that's right.
But at that point, you went by train to Austin and to?
Train to Baylor, Waco.
Waco, did you go to either Dallas or Fort Worth that year, the year you were there?
I don't believe we did that my freshman year.
I have been on those later.
One of the things to us was, it takes A&M.
the kush or pie or dessert, it seemed to us that everybody had all the raisin pie they wanted.
And we had a boy from Maryland, who shall remain nameless, they gave us a meal ticket at Waco, the merchants did, to buy, and we could buy anything we wanted to to eat.
And one of the Texas A&M boys bought a
Raisin pie, and I guess till his dying day, he lived to regret that.
We never let him forget.
Okay, back to the typical day then.
Did you reform your companies to go to supper?
We reformed, made a formation to march to supper.
We marched supper and came back, and then we were supposed to be in our room.
Once again, we could amble back to the room, but there was usually some sophomore that wanted us to come back and see him for some reason or another.
And we had to be in our room, I'm going to say, by 7 or 8 o'clock.
And we were supposed to be in our room then until 1045.
And then from 1045 to 11, we could do anything in the world we wanted to or go anywhere we wanted to just so we didn't leave the campus for 15 minutes.
And then what?
Like that?
And then 11 nights out at 11.
That was a typical day.
Of course, there's lots of variations because some nights they were aired out or threats of being aired out.
I don't know that we had too many.
We were...
I happened to be in Foster Hall in Fish Heaven.

There were, it's the fourth floor of Foster Hall and there was no one lived up there but freshmen and they called it Fish Heaven so they didn't want to climb those steps and get after us too much but there was always that threat of we were going to get aired out.
It seemed like it every night, of course it wasn't.
And we got somewhere out of place and we were drowned out too, a time or two.
What about, did they have a midnight yell practice or anything of that nature?
Yes, the midnight yell practice was really a scary experience.
The first time I experienced it, Dutch Horn came to town and
That was my first knowledge of that great old man.
And he told us all about how A&M was going to dogs because it was going to let girls in it.
This was in 1924.
And he told us some of the pitfalls of girls at Texas A&M University.
And we had a lot of fun.
I said it would be all right.
We'd go back to her room whenever we wanted to.
And I don't know whether it took an hour and a half out of her life or what.
But anyway, it was really some experience to go to those midnight Yale practices.
I can't remember whether I have been pretty well associated with Texas A&M.
And I have been to their.
were a fallen comrade.
What is that called?
Silver taps?
Silver taps.
I've been to those and I can't remember whether as a freshman I had those or not.
But it's a very impressive ceremony and I have been to them through the years and I know and I can't, my memory failed me whether I had one as a freshman or not.
But I know I've always been impressed with silver taps.
You mentioned a minute ago that you lived the year you were there in the fourth floor of Foster Hall in Fish Heaven.
What was life like?
I mean, was it pretty wild and woolly at times in the dormitory?
Oh, yes, it was wild and woolly.
There was almost never a dull moment.
The other fish in the company knew that they'd come up there and not be molested by the sophomores, or that was the assumption.
And we had a lot of visitors up there that were freshmen.
And also, it had its misgivings in the fact that when a sophomore wanted a freshman, he knew where to find one.
One of my things I started with when I first went to Texas A&M was I went in my room and locked my door.
And of course, that's a fallacy.
There's no way you can lock a door in Texas A&M that I knew of.
Because someone could get a bayonet and come right on in as if
Of course, that's one of the first things I learned, too, is how to get in another room.
I think that is part of the Aggie tradition about the openness.
There's no way you can, as they say now, a man can be an island unto himself because it takes saying him.
There wasn't any such thing as privacy.
I don't mean that they meddled in everyone's business, but your door was open.
Well, I visited A&M campus a number of times when I was an undergraduate at Texas Lutheran, and I was always impressed by two things.
One, the friendliness of the students.
And two, the fact that a student could put down almost anything anywhere and come back any time later and they'd still be there.
That's right.
And the last three years I observed and kind of feel that unfortunately neither of those are quite as true as they used to be.
The friendliness is there on occasion, but of course certainly you're not greeted by everybody as you were when it was an all-military school.
And I think there's a little bit of reluctance to put something down, and he clicked to come back an hour later and find it.
It's an unforgivable sin not to speak to anyone at Texas A&M, of course.
One of the first things you learn is to introduce yourself.
We learned was to introduce yourself to everyone else.
My first experience along that line,
I introduced myself to a man, and I told him Fish Ansley was my name.
Incidentally, my name was Fish Ansley for the entire freshman year, which at first it kind of stung, but I learned to be awful proud of it.
This sophomore says, Fish Ansley, you've met me before.
And I says, no, I haven't, sir.
He says, well, you've been over it.
And I'll show you what my name is.
His name happened to be Harry A. Holzer, Jr.
I shall never forget that name, and he would be named Junior.
And now it's 50 years ago that this happened, and I still know Harry A. Holzer, Jr., because he spelled it out with each letter with a board.
It's been a very valuable lesson to me through life.

I have, when I'm introduced to anyone, I pay attention to their name now, because if you get, that happened to me one other occasion, but the man's name wasn't that long, so it wouldn't make that big an impression on me, but I have learned to pay attention, which is very valuable.
It's nothing but courteous that I found that, and I appreciate that fact.
I must say that we were isolated.
Texas A&M College, at the time I was there, was isolated, meaning the only way we had through civilization, which was Brian, was by trolley car.
We called it the Tunerville Trolley.
And of course, freshmen couldn't go but one day a week, and that was Sunday unless we sneaked off or something.
We always, there was always something to do.
Of course sophomores thought that too, that he did, but you, of course you can always study a little bit.
What sorts of things did the sophomores have you do for them?
Oh, let's see.
Of course we cleaned up sophomores' rooms.
We became their maids in a way of, I don't know whether that's what they called them or not.
The term dog robber was still in use when I was at school and we almost became their dog robber.
When they wanted to borrow candy from Casey's, they just stuck their head out the door and hollered freshman and you were supposed to go down and they'd go.
You go get them the bar of candy or anything else that they might desire.
I thought it was terrible at the time, but I can't remember anything that they ever made me do that rankled me much.
Of course, we went to the post office for them.
There's only one post office there.
Then it was in the back of one of the Air Force dormitories.
Did you ever have to do things like carry their laundry over?
Yeah, we carried their clothes to the laundry.
We were kind of almost maids in a way.
You had to sweep out the room and make the bed?
Did you have to make the bed every day?
Every day, every morning.
We made their beds, which has become a pretty good...

business for me in later years when my wife kind of liked the fact that i could make a bed i i must hesitate to say here those people that gave me the most chores and and gave me the most hell turned out to be my greatest friends they were the people that would have done anything in the world for me and and i still revere them to this day
This is a form of hazing.
It's kind of like your parents.
It's a form of hazing that you need because I don't believe, I must say right here, I don't know of anybody in the world that was as smart as I was when I went to Texas A&M.
I knew everything in the world.
It wasn't old, I thought.
But I take it you learned pretty quickly.
You didn't know everything.
I sure did.
I wondered how those people could tell that I was a freshman.
because I'd come from a bigger town than one of the larger towns in the state down there, and those were just old country boys, and how in the world they could tell I was a freshman.
They made me wear a fish stripe, which would put a white stripe around my left wrist, at the shirt, and on the shirt, and they called that a fish stripe, and of course I didn't need that because
They could tell I was a fish as if I had a neon sign six blocks off.
They knew I was a fish, as we all later learned.
You can tell a fish just as far as you can see.
What was the food like in the mess hall?
Well, I gained 15 pounds the first 15 days I was at Texas A&M.
I'm sure that, as I say, I did a little running around when I was at home.
And I got down to A&M, and we had regular food and regular hours.
And I went from 155 pounds to 170 pounds in 15 days.
And I have never been able to criticize the food at Texas A&M.
Now, I know some people that didn't do that way, but it wasn't that way with me.
And I still.
have thoughts of apricot pie.
Most people used to call pineapple kush.
They thought that was the greatest thing in the world.
It's fresh, but it was apricot kush with me.
I really and truly, I've never found any apricot pie that tastes that good again.
Well, who was in the mess hall then when you were there?
Duncan.
Duncan.
Did they have a number of students working in there?
Yes, they had a lot of students working.
Waiting tables?
Waiting tables.
Washing dishes?
And I don't know why I said they called those mess hall hounds.
What?
No, meal hounds, what they called the boys that ate too much.
I've forgotten what they called.
Sabezas.
It's been so long ago that I can't remember whether I'd ever seen...
ever saw Mr. Spieser, but Duncan was there at the time.
I can't remember, but I think Duncan succeeded Spieser.
Yes, that's right.
One of my fondest memories is of Charlie Nitsch.
Charlie Nitsch was, I'm going to say, an Italian alien or immigrant to this country.
He ran the tailor shop there, and he
was kind of a point of ridicule.
Of course, I never dreamed that I would end up in the dry cleaning business for my life's work after Charlie and Itch.
We used to kind of kid quite a bit about Charlie and Itch down there.
He ran the tailor shop?
He ran the tailor shop.
Of course, when your uniforms were issued to you, it seemed that they never fit.
So you had to go down to Charlie and Itch and get them all.
fitted so everybody got to know Charlie niche one way or another and you mentioned earlier that say the fish could go to town what once once a week once a Sunday or Saturday or Sunday what what
privileges in addition to that, say, did an upperclassman have?
Could a sophomore go to town more often than that?
I don't believe the sophomores were supposed to go any often than that.
Of course, the juniors and seniors almost had to free run the campus.
I believe the sophomores were just about as supposed to stay on the campus about as much as freshmen.
And so, but the only means of transportation out of there was either this trolley or the train.
That's right.
It was the Houston and Texas Central and, uh...
The line, that's the Jenny.
Now let's see, what do they call it?
The INGN.
Yeah, International Great Northern was the other one that ran through there.
Uh, I must say right here that I see you've interviewed Harold Dunn.
Uh, his hamburger stand was, I don't know if he spoke to you about it or not, but it was truly an oasis on the campus.
And I've stood in line many a time for hamburgers from upperclassmen and also from myself.
That's another one of the chores we used to do to get some of Harold Unn's hamburgers.
He talked a little bit about his hamburger stand.
